and that's how we came about. How about you, Ning? Yeah, Jing, I totally agree. I think like starting

00:22:11.060 --> 00:22:15.300
from something concrete, and I think like Jing, you and me also discussed a little bit on like

00:22:15.300 --> 00:22:20.099
whether we, it's a matter of bringing data together, or it's a matter of bringing the people

00:22:20.099 --> 00:22:25.459
together, like the data scientists together. Yeah, I think I resonate in that a lot, because like

00:22:25.459 --> 00:22:32.260
Roche is a huge company, and it's impossible to bring other data together. Like even combining

00:22:32.260 --> 00:22:38.099
more kind of integrating data from clinical trials, which seem like a straightforward task,

00:22:38.099 --> 00:22:44.579
is not that easy. So it's actually a huge task over there. On the other side, I feel like a

00:22:44.579 --> 00:22:50.739
quick win, like to Jing's point, is maybe bringing the data scientists together. For example, in Roche,

00:22:51.699 --> 00:22:57.060
like in pharma, like we have data scientists varying different heights. There are people who

00:22:57.060 --> 00:23:02.260
are really, really good at clinical trial design, clinical trial data analysis. There are people

00:23:02.260 --> 00:23:06.660
really good at real-world data analysis. There are people really good at genomic analysis,

00:23:06.660 --> 00:23:14.420
and sometimes we see that like actually like each person is only kind of like representing their own

00:23:14.420 --> 00:23:21.380
kind of like specialty, and then they only share their results like to the stakeholders,

00:23:21.380 --> 00:23:26.500
for example, clinicians. And then for the clinicians, actually it could be confusing

00:23:26.500 --> 00:23:31.459
if the clinician like see some result from real-world data, some result from clinical

00:23:31.459 --> 00:23:38.180
trial data, some result from biomarker data, and we all know that there is no 100% consistency

00:23:38.180 --> 00:23:43.459
like across different data sources, like all the models are wrong, all the data's are wrong. Yeah,

00:23:43.459 --> 00:23:51.060
so kind of how to triangulate, navigate through those data sources is not an expertise from the

00:23:51.060 --> 00:23:57.699
clinicians, from our stakeholders. Actually, it is our expertise. It's an expertise like of data

00:23:57.699 --> 00:24:04.660
science to really kind of like take all those diverse results in and find an interpretation

00:24:04.660 --> 00:24:09.699
in acknowledging the limitation of each data sources. So yeah, one thing we try to kind of like

00:24:10.339 --> 00:24:16.819
like encourage our people to do is bring those data scientists together and then kind of have

00:24:16.819 --> 00:24:23.380
this like data science team. In some cases, there is a data science team leader who can really like

00:24:23.380 --> 00:24:30.500
bring those data together and share to our stakeholders an actionable interpretation

00:24:30.500 --> 00:24:37.219
or even some options for development rather than just say, hey, there are like 20 pages report,

00:24:37.219 --> 00:24:43.780
go read it and figure out how to do with it. Yeah. And I can maybe add one thing. I was in a,

00:24:43.780 --> 00:24:50.500
you know, senior leadership on the data science forum. We talked about and the common theme

00:24:51.060 --> 00:25:00.979
is it may sound mundane, but when we say bring data together, it is very worthwhile to figure

00:25:00.979 --> 00:25:06.579
out for each stakeholder what that means. And you will be very surprised that actually

00:25:06.579 --> 00:25:12.099
may mean a very different thing. One person may be meaning we have to standardize literally into

00:25:12.099 --> 00:25:19.300
one database. One person may be, oh, I just need the data could be linked together. They could be

00:25:19.300 --> 00:25:25.459
conjoined, whatever. I don't care where they sit. It could be even further loose, as Ning said. I

00:25:25.459 --> 00:25:31.619
just need different data scientists at different sites to be able to access so they can analyze

00:25:31.699 --> 00:25:38.099
the data. So what bring data together means figure out that understanding difference.

00:25:38.739 --> 00:25:44.099
And then as a data science leader, you come in for that specific problem to say,

00:25:44.660 --> 00:25:51.060
what makes the best sense for this particular project? Right. Then you educate all the

00:25:52.420 --> 00:25:59.619
cross-functional stakeholder to say, I know you initially saw means this, but for this project,

00:25:59.619 --> 00:26:08.420
because of ABC, we really need to do either just this or more this, right, to enable the project to

00:26:08.420 --> 00:26:14.579
go forward. That really help establish your technical leadership and strategic leadership,

00:26:14.579 --> 00:26:20.099
because the cross-functional leader is very important for them to feel they have been heard.

00:26:20.900 --> 00:26:27.459
Instead of we just rush into our own assumption, they were like, what? This is not what I saw,

00:26:27.459 --> 00:26:33.699
what data together even means, right? So spend the time at the beginning to do this

00:26:34.420 --> 00:26:40.420
understanding alignment will benefit tremendously down the road.

00:26:43.459 --> 00:26:51.619
Maybe real quick here on this nodding head problem. If you do find yourself in a meeting

00:26:52.260 --> 00:26:56.099
where that's happening, I know there's all the things we could do before, but how do you

00:26:56.660 --> 00:27:04.099
address it and stop that? I can also chime in, right? It depends on things, right? If it is

00:27:04.099 --> 00:27:11.540
really just, oh, bring to the awareness, bring data intelligence across functions without a

00:27:12.579 --> 00:27:18.260
need for a concrete output, nodding head is great. Then you follow up with a quick survey, oh,

00:27:18.260 --> 00:27:23.859
90% support, right? That's just wrapping the project up. It's a great success. We increase

00:27:23.859 --> 00:27:30.500
the awareness. However, if it's an urgent project, I think instead of relying on other people to be

00:27:30.500 --> 00:27:36.739
a strategic leader, we have to step up to do more things technical. I encourage my team members,

00:27:36.739 --> 00:27:44.660
including myself, we have action item beforehand. We say, if you agree, please do this, this, this

00:27:44.660 --> 00:27:50.020
by this week, right? Or if you need to review, here's the timeframe we can answer question,

00:27:50.099 --> 00:27:55.859
blah, blah, blah, blah. But we expect you to take this action by this time if you agree with the

00:27:55.859 --> 00:28:02.500
general plan. If you have other thing you need to sort out, clarify, whatever, we are here to help,

00:28:02.500 --> 00:28:08.420
right? And then you have a framework, a timeframe. Then you kind of start nudging people. Like you

00:28:08.420 --> 00:28:12.900
said, you're going to deliver three weeks. That's what we decided in this meeting, followed by

00:28:12.900 --> 00:28:21.300
meeting minutes, where's the progress, right? So you start the framework that will help make

00:28:22.260 --> 00:28:29.060
everybody accountable instead of just nodding head, right? You start, you prepare ahead of time,

00:28:29.060 --> 00:28:33.939
like what is required, implied by you nodding your head.

00:28:34.660 --> 00:28:39.459
Yeah, I totally agree. I also feel like sometimes when I talk to my team, like, yeah, sometimes I

00:28:39.459 --> 00:28:45.140
also see myself and including myself, some of my team members, like we have the perception that we

00:28:45.140 --> 00:28:50.579
will present this problem to a meeting and magically in the meeting, someone will chime in

00:28:50.579 --> 00:28:56.739
and find a solution. But 90% of the time, it won't happen because for people in the meeting,

00:28:56.739 --> 00:29:02.579
they only think about this specific problem for like 30 minutes, an hour. And you have been

00:29:02.579 --> 00:29:07.859
thinking about this problem probably for weeks and months. And if you don't have a very clear,

00:29:07.859 --> 00:29:13.380
to Jing's point, if you don't have a very clear kind of like expected outcome or expected next

00:29:13.380 --> 00:29:18.739
step, like for this project that no one in the meeting will come up with a better plan over there.

