versus business saying this is the priority? I can provide, because our product is machine

00:44:20.899 --> 00:44:27.540
learning models. So it is – I will say in the most healthy organization, I certainly believe

00:44:27.540 --> 00:44:35.860
Verisight is one. It's never one or the other. It's a joint one, right? So usually it's an iterative

00:44:35.860 --> 00:44:44.260
process. We say, hey, let's just start, right? Like one example, hey, you know, our commercial

00:44:44.260 --> 00:44:50.100
folks will come say to say we continuously hear feedback to say it would be really helpful to add

00:44:50.100 --> 00:44:55.459
a feature to our product, right? Or they will come say, well, it would be really helpful to add A and

00:44:55.459 --> 00:45:01.219
B and C to our product all at once, right? Then we'll say, hey, guess what? From a data science

00:45:01.219 --> 00:45:06.659
point of view, A needs six months development you can deploy. B needs about two years. C,

00:45:06.659 --> 00:45:11.780
we are uncertain. We need to do phased approach, right? What is the investment? Remember finance

00:45:11.780 --> 00:45:17.939
people is in the leadership. What is investment in each? What is the ROI? What is uncertainty?

00:45:17.939 --> 00:45:24.419
Let's decide as a team, right? And then, you know, that's the initial data evidence we provide with

00:45:24.419 --> 00:45:31.219
our expertise, right? How long it will take to develop? How long, you know, how large is the

00:45:31.219 --> 00:45:36.739
investment? And then the commercial come back to say, guess what? Now I see A, B, C. Each will

00:45:36.739 --> 00:45:43.540
give us how much more revenue or volume increase or stickiness from the customer. This is what we

00:45:43.540 --> 00:45:48.739
get. And then with that two piece of information, we decide to say, hey, maybe sometimes it's a

00:45:48.739 --> 00:45:54.020
selection. Let's just try B because it's so quick. Or they will say, let's try B and A at the same

00:45:54.020 --> 00:46:01.139
time and hire more people because it sounds so important. So it's really a dynamic, cross-functional

00:46:01.139 --> 00:46:10.979
decision for our business. Yeah, I agree with Jing. I also feel like it's rarely A versus B,

00:46:10.979 --> 00:46:18.260
like kind of like a functional interest versus business need. Often it has both components.

00:46:18.260 --> 00:46:22.979
Yeah. So from Roche, like we are actually, our culture actually encourage a lot of grassroot

00:46:22.979 --> 00:46:28.739
effort. So we encourage people to innovate in their daily work. So there are a lot of ideas

00:46:28.739 --> 00:46:35.939
popping up and et cetera. And oftentimes those ideas are coming from actual study need. And then

00:46:35.939 --> 00:46:41.620
to the earlier point, there are the things people feel bored about, like the repetitive work,

00:46:41.620 --> 00:46:47.300
et cetera. Yeah. So oftentimes those are from actual need. And a larger question is some of

00:46:47.300 --> 00:46:53.620
those needs are only tied with one particular project or one particular study. Some of them

00:46:53.620 --> 00:47:00.580
are applicable for the whole portfolio or across different projects, et cetera. So I feel like

00:47:00.580 --> 00:47:06.739
what our leadership team try to do is basically still encourage innovation, but if they see any

00:47:06.739 --> 00:47:13.219
kind of innovation and they see an innovation that can be applied as an amplifier across a

00:47:13.219 --> 00:47:18.899
large number of projects, then they give a push to this project. Yeah. So that kind of like taking

00:47:18.899 --> 00:47:24.419
an example from myself, actually, when I joined Roche about eight years ago, I was about statistician.

00:47:24.419 --> 00:47:29.540
So I was working on clinical trials, like doing design, doing clinical trial reporting. And at

00:47:29.540 --> 00:47:35.780
that time I realized that there is opportunity for us to adopt open source languages and do better

00:47:35.780 --> 00:47:41.780
code sharing, code standardization, et cetera. So actually it was kind of like my hobby project

00:47:41.860 --> 00:47:48.899
for several years until maybe like three, four years ago. In Roche, we decided to double down

00:47:48.899 --> 00:47:56.500
to this strategy of adopting open source tools and platforms. And then this became my day job.

00:47:56.500 --> 00:48:03.459
Yeah. So I think like, yeah, kind of like there is definitely a kind of like incubation period,

00:48:03.459 --> 00:48:09.300
but like from our company, we encourage like all the new ideas from the grassroots efforts. Yeah.

00:48:09.300 --> 00:48:11.860
Yeah. Thank you.

00:48:15.060 --> 00:48:21.139
Thank you so much. So I always like to sneak this question in, but is there a piece of

00:48:21.139 --> 00:48:26.340
career advice that you've received or that you've given others that you'd like to share with us?

