I can start. So we usually are very technical. This is about communication,

00:48:37.300 --> 00:48:43.379
just to set the context. We're usually very technical people, but the audience sometimes,

00:48:43.379 --> 00:48:49.939
especially for strategic decisions, are usually not technical people. Sometimes we want to be

00:48:49.939 --> 00:48:58.979
so rigorous, we say or claim humbly that add 20 caveat, right? Does the 20 caveat really need to

00:48:58.979 --> 00:49:06.179
be said in the meeting? So I always say, really think about the audience. It's rarely that

00:49:06.179 --> 00:49:12.260
important what you're about to say or what you said is about what they hear, right? What do you

00:49:12.260 --> 00:49:20.260
want to get out of that conversation, right? Then structure your communication. Be more confident

00:49:20.260 --> 00:49:26.100
on the positive claim if there is one, right? Maybe put the caveat in the no section.

00:49:26.659 --> 00:49:32.979
You are no longer a student. You don't have to be demonstrate your capability. We hired you.

00:49:32.979 --> 00:49:38.899
That's already enough. You should demonstrate what the result means. What is the next step,

00:49:38.899 --> 00:49:44.739
right? How I can move the business forward? What is the impact to each cross-functional leaders

00:49:44.739 --> 00:49:51.699
beyond the technical caveat and technical details, right? So that's always a communication tip

00:49:51.699 --> 00:49:57.939
I give people who work as a data scientist or in data analytics in the industry setting.

00:49:58.580 --> 00:50:05.139
I really like that. And I know from BBSW conference, we also talk about this decision

00:50:05.139 --> 00:50:13.379
size, like my side. So basically, to James' point, I think the main goal is enable decisions,

00:50:13.379 --> 00:50:19.379
is to enable actions. It's not showcasing our capability that I can generate 200 outputs

00:50:19.379 --> 00:50:23.780
over there or showcasing that I can do a really complex model over there. It's really enable

00:50:24.739 --> 00:50:31.139
the next decision. And I remember I was reading a book called The Manager's Path. And on one

00:50:31.139 --> 00:50:37.300
section, it's saying, how do you manage your one-on-ones with your manager? I think in my

00:50:37.300 --> 00:50:44.020
